hints_latex:
Justify to yourself that it suffices to find an \emph{n} so that

\begin{align*}
\frac{K(b-a)^5}{180n^4} = \frac{60}{180n^{4}} \leq 0.001
\end{align*}

Don't forget that \emph{n} has to be even! (By the constraints of
Simpson's rule)

statement_latex:
Let

\begin{align*}
I = \int_0^1 \cos(x^2)\,dx
\end{align*}

It can be shown that the 4th derivative of

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \cos(x^2)
\end{align*} has absolute value at most 60 on the
interval {[}0,1{]}. Using this bound, find the smallest positive integer
\emph{n} you can such that the Simpson's Rule approximation $S_n$ for
$I$ has error less or equal to 0.001. You may use the fact that if

\begin{align*}
|f^{(4)}(t)| \leq K
\end{align*} on the interval $[a\text{, }b]$, then the error
in using $S_n$ to approximate

\begin{align*}
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx
\end{align*} has absolute value less than or equal to

\begin{align*}
\frac{K(b-a)^5}{180n^4}
\end{align*}
